FAQ
Why is Base's upfront cost so low?

At Base, we're developing a battery network to enhance the power grid's stability by discharging, or selling, at times of peak need. By installing a battery at your home, you contribute to this network, and in return, we offer backup power without high upfront costs.

How much backup power will I have?

Backup duration varies by home size and power consumption, but Baseâ€™s battery typically provides up to 1 day of backup for most homes. This is enough to withstand the large majority of outages.

Where is Base available? 

Base operates in â€œderegulatedâ€ areas of Texas where you can select your own provider, including regions serviced by Oncor, Centerpoint, TNMP, and AEP. Enter your address to learn about your homeâ€™s eligibility, or check your meter to see if has one of these names.

What is the total cost of a Base system? How much will I pay monthly?

The cost includes a one-time $1,500 installation fee plus a monthly energy fee based on your usage. Your unit rate (price per kWh) will be communicated when your battery is ready for installation.
â€

What happens if I move?

If you move, the battery remains and the contract transfers to the new owner. A new installation is needed for your new home.

Can I be a Base customer if I have solar?

Base batteries can integrate seamlessly with solar panels, enhancing the value and efficiency of solar. This means your home will remain powered for even longer periods of time.

Does the Base system require maintenance?

Base batteries are designed to be reliable and resilient. Homeowners don't need to perform any maintenance on the Base battery system.

How long will the battery last?

Base batteries are designed to last over 15 years, but could last even more than that depending on charge and discharge cycles.
